variants.name: Unbonded
docs: A member has unbonded from their pool.
- `balance` is the corresponding balance of the number of points that has been
requested to be unbonded (the argument of the `unbond` transaction) from the bonded
pool.
- `points` is the number of points that are issued as a result of `balance` being
dissolved into the corresponding unbonding pool.
- `era` is the era in which the balance will be unbonded.
In the absence of slashing, these values will match. In the presence of slashing, the
number of points that are issued in the unbonding pool will be less than the amount
requested to be unbonded.

variants.name: Withdrawn
docs: A member has withdrawn from their pool.
The given number of `points` have been dissolved in return of `balance`.
Similar to `Unbonded` event, in the absence of slashing, the ratio of point to balance
will be 1.

docs: The epoch randomness for the *current* epoch.
# Security
This MUST NOT be used for gambling, as it can be influenced by a
malicious validator in the short term. It MAY be used in many
cryptographic protocols, however, so long as one remembers that this
(like everything else on-chain) it is public. For example, it can be
used where a number is needed that cannot have been chosen by an

Once a segment reaches this length, we begin the next one.
We reset all segments and return to `0` at the beginning of every
epoch.

constants.name: OperationalFeeMultiplier
docs: A fee multiplier for `Operational` extrinsics to compute "virtual tip" to boost their
`priority`
This value is multiplied by the `final_fee` to obtain a "virtual tip" that is later
added to a tip component in regular `priority` calculations.
It means that a `Normal` transaction can front-run a similarly-sized `Operational`
extrinsic (with no tip), by including a tip value greater than the virtual tip.
```rust,ignore
// For `Normal`
let priority = priority_calc(tip);
// For `Operational`
let virtual_tip = (inclusion_fee + tip) * OperationalFeeMultiplier;
let priority = priority_calc(tip + virtual_tip);
Note that since we use `final_fee` the multiplier applies also to the regular `tip`
sent with the transaction. So, not only does the transaction get a priority bump based
on the `inclusion_fee`, but we also amplify the impact of tips applied to `Operational`
transactions.

items.name: SignedSubmissionNextIndex
docs: The next index to be assigned to an incoming signed submission.
Every accepted submission is assigned a unique index; that index is bound to that particular
submission for the duration of the election. On election finalization, the next index is
reset to 0.
We can't just use `SignedSubmissionIndices.len()`, because that's a bounded set; past its
capacity, it will simply saturate. We can't just iterate over `SignedSubmissionsMap`,
because iteration is slow. Instead, we store the value here.

items.name: SignedSubmissionIndices
docs: A sorted, bounded vector of `(score, block_number, index)`, where each `index` points to a
value in `SignedSubmissions`.
We never need to process more than a single signed submission at a time. Signed submissions
can be quite large, so we're willing to pay the cost of multiple database accesses to access
them one at a time instead of reading and decoding all of them at once.

items.name: SignedSubmissionsMap
docs: Unchecked, signed solutions.
Together with `SubmissionIndices`, this stores a bounded set of `SignedSubmissions` while
allowing us to keep only a single one in memory at a time.
Twox note: the key of the map is an auto-incrementing index which users cannot inspect or
affect; we shouldn't need a cryptographically secure hasher.

items.name: Nominators
docs: The map from nominator stash key to their nomination preferences, namely the validators that
they wish to support.
Note that the keys of this storage map might become non-decodable in case the
account's [`NominationsQuota::MaxNominations`] configuration is decreased.
In this rare case, these nominators
are still existent in storage, their key is correct and retrievable (i.e. `contains_key`
indicates that they exist), but their value cannot be decoded. Therefore, the non-decodable
nominators will effectively not-exist, until they re-submit their preferences such that it
is within the bounds of the newly set `Config::MaxNominations`.
This implies that `::iter_keys().count()` and `::iter().count()` might return different
values for this map. Moreover, the main `::count()` is aligned with the former, namely the
number of keys that exist.
Lastly, if any of the nominators become non-decodable, they can be chilled immediately via
[`Call::chill_other`] dispatchable by anyone.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE since `AccountId` is a secure hash.

This contains the total stake in support of the validator and their own stake. In addition,
it can also be used to get the number of nominators backing this validator and the number of
exposure pages they are divided into. The page count is useful to determine the number of
pages of rewards that needs to be claimed.
This is keyed first by the era index to allow bulk deletion and then the stash account.
Should only be accessed through `EraInfo`.
Is it removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If stakers hasn't been set or has been removed then empty overview is returned.

Note: This is deprecated, should be used as read-only and will be removed in the future.
New `Exposure`s are stored in a paged manner in `ErasStakersPaged` instead.
This is similar to [`ErasStakers`] but number of nominators exposed is reduced to the
`T::MaxExposurePageSize` biggest stakers.
(Note: the field `total` and `own` of the exposure remains unchanged).
This is used to limit the i/o cost for the nominator payout.
This is keyed fist by the era index to allow bulk deletion and then the stash account.
It is removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If stakers hasn't been set or has been removed then empty exposure is returned.
Note: Deprecated since v14. Use `EraInfo` instead to work with exposures.

Eras that haven't finished yet or has been removed doesn't have reward.

items.name: ErasRewardPoints
docs: Rewards for the last [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If reward hasn't been set or has been removed then 0 reward is returned.

items.name: ErasTotalStake
docs: The total amount staked for the last [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If total hasn't been set or has been removed then 0 stake is returned.

items.name: ForceEra
docs: Mode of era forcing.

items.name: SlashRewardFraction
docs: The percentage of the slash that is distributed to reporters.
The rest of the slashed value is handled by the `Slash`.

items.name: CanceledSlashPayout
docs: The amount of currency given to reporters of a slash event which was
canceled by extraordinary circumstances (e.g. governance).

items.name: UnappliedSlashes
docs: All unapplied slashes that are queued for later.

items.name: BondedEras
docs: A mapping from still-bonded eras to the first session index of that era.
Must contains information for eras for the range:
`[active_era - bounding_duration; active_era]`

items.name: ValidatorSlashInEra
docs: All slashing events on validators, mapped by era to the highest slash proportion
and slash value of the era.

items.name: NominatorSlashInEra
docs: All slashing events on nominators, mapped by era to the highest slash value of the era.

items.name: SlashingSpans
docs: Slashing spans for stash accounts.

items.name: SpanSlash
docs: Records information about the maximum slash of a stash within a slashing span,
as well as how much reward has been paid out.

items.name: CurrentPlannedSession
docs: The last planned session scheduled by the session pallet.
This is basically in sync with the call to [`pallet_session::SessionManager::new_session`].

items.name: OffendingValidators
docs: Indices of validators that have offended in the active era and whether they are currently
disabled.
This value should be a superset of disabled validators since not all offences lead to the
validator being disabled (if there was no slash). This is needed to track the percentage of
validators that have offended in the current era, ensuring a new era is forced if
`OffendingValidatorsThreshold` is reached. The vec is always kept sorted so that we can find
whether a given validator has previously offended using binary search. It gets cleared when
the era ends.

items.name: ChillThreshold
docs: The threshold for when users can start calling `chill_other` for other validators /
nominators. The threshold is compared to the actual number of validators / nominators
(`CountFor*`) in the system compared to the configured max (`Max*Count`).

constants.name: HistoryDepth
docs: Number of eras to keep in history.
Following information is kept for eras in `[current_era -
HistoryDepth, current_era]`: `ErasStakers`, `ErasStakersClipped`,
`ErasValidatorPrefs`, `ErasValidatorReward`, `ErasRewardPoints`,
`ErasTotalStake`, `ErasStartSessionIndex`, `ClaimedRewards`, `ErasStakersPaged`,
`ErasStakersOverview`.
Must be more than the number of eras delayed by session.
I.e. active era must always be in history. I.e. `active_era >
current_era - history_depth` must be guaranteed.
If migrating an existing pallet from storage value to config value,
this should be set to same value or greater as in storage.
Note: `HistoryDepth` is used as the upper bound for the `BoundedVec`
item `StakingLedger.legacy_claimed_rewards`. Setting this value lower than
the existing value can lead to inconsistencies in the
`StakingLedger` and will need to be handled properly in a migration.
The test `reducing_history_depth_abrupt` shows this effect.

constants.name: SessionsPerEra
docs: Number of sessions per era.

constants.name: BondingDuration
docs: Number of eras that staked funds must remain bonded for.

constants.name: SlashDeferDuration
docs: Number of eras that slashes are deferred by, after computation.
This should be less than the bonding duration. Set to 0 if slashes
should be applied immediately, without opportunity for intervention.

constants.name: MaxExposurePageSize
docs: The maximum size of each `T::ExposurePage`.
An `ExposurePage` is weakly bounded to a maximum of `MaxExposurePageSize`
nominators.
For older non-paged exposure, a reward payout was restricted to the top
`MaxExposurePageSize` nominators. This is to limit the i/o cost for the
nominator payout.
Note: `MaxExposurePageSize` is used to bound `ClaimedRewards` and is unsafe to reduce
without handling it in a migration.

constants.name: MaxUnlockingChunks
docs: The maximum number of `unlocking` chunks a [`StakingLedger`] can
have. Effectively determines how many unique eras a staker may be
unbonding in.
Note: `MaxUnlockingChunks` is used as the upper bound for the
`BoundedVec` item `StakingLedger.unlocking`. Setting this value
lower than the existing value can lead to inconsistencies in the
`StakingLedger` and will need to be handled properly in a runtime
migration. The test `reducing_max_unlocking_chunks_abrupt` shows
this effect.

items.name: QueuedChanged

has changed in the queued validator set.

items.name: QueuedKeys

will be used to determine the validator's session keys.

items.name: DisabledValidators

disabled using binary search. It gets cleared when `on_session_ending` returns

docs: The next free referendum index, aka the number of referenda started so far.

items.name: LowestUnbaked
docs: The lowest referendum index representing an unbaked referendum. Equal to
`ReferendumCount` if there isn't a unbaked referendum.

items.name: ReferendumInfoOf
docs: Information concerning any given referendum.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE as indexes are not under an attackers control.

items.name: VotingOf
docs: All votes for a particular voter. We store the balance for the number of votes that we
have recorded. The second item is the total amount of delegations, that will be added.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE as `AccountId`s are crypto hashes anyway.

docs: True if the last referendum tabled was submitted externally. False if it was a public
proposal.

items.name: NextExternal
docs: The referendum to be tabled whenever it would be valid to table an external proposal.
This happens when a referendum needs to be tabled and one of two conditions are met:
- `LastTabledWasExternal` is `false`; or
- `PublicProps` is empty.

docs: A record of who vetoed what. Maps proposal hash to a possible existent block number
(until when it may not be resubmitted) and who vetoed it.

items.name: Cancellations

items.name: MetadataOf
docs: General information concerning any proposal or referendum.
The `Hash` refers to the preimage of the `Preimages` provider which can be a JSON
dump or IPFS hash of a JSON file.
Consider a garbage collection for a metadata of finished referendums to `unrequest` (remove)
large preimages.

constants.name: EnactmentPeriod
docs: The period between a proposal being approved and enacted.
It should generally be a little more than the unstake period to ensure that
voting stakers have an opportunity to remove themselves from the system in the case
where they are on the losing side of a vote.

constants.name: VotingPeriod

constants.name: VoteLockingPeriod
docs: The minimum period of vote locking.

those successful voters are locked into the consequences that their votes entail.

constants.name: MinimumDeposit

constants.name: InstantAllowed

want to set this permanently to `false`, others may want to condition it on things such
as an upgrade having happened recently.

constants.name: FastTrackVotingPeriod

constants.name: CooloffPeriod
docs: Period in blocks where an external proposal may not be re-submitted after being vetoed.

constants.name: MaxVotes
docs: The maximum number of votes for an account.
Also used to compute weight, an overly big value can
lead to extrinsic with very big weight: see `delegate` for instance.

constants.name: MaxProposals

constants.name: MaxDeposits

constants.name: MaxBlacklisted
docs: The maximum number of items which can be blacklisted.

constants.name: VotingBondBase
docs: Base deposit associated with voting.
This should be sensibly high to economically ensure the pallet cannot be attacked by
creating a gigantic number of votes.

round will happen. If set to zero, no elections are ever triggered and the module will
be in passive mode.

docs: The maximum number of candidates in a phragmen election.
Warning: This impacts the size of the election which is run onchain. Chose wisely, and
consider how it will impact `T::WeightInfo::election_phragmen`.
When this limit is reached no more candidates are accepted in the election.

constants.name: MaxVoters

Warning: This impacts the size of the election which is run onchain. Chose wisely, and
consider how it will impact `T::WeightInfo::election_phragmen`.
When the limit is reached the new voters are ignored.

constants.name: MaxVotesPerVoter
docs: Maximum numbers of votes per voter.
Warning: This impacts the size of the election which is run onchain. Chose wisely, and
consider how it will impact `T::WeightInfo::election_phragmen`.

items.name: Members
docs: The current membership, stored as an ordered Vec.

items.name: Prime
docs: The current prime member, if one exists.

items.name: State
docs: State of the current authority set.

items.name: PendingChange
docs: Pending change: (signaled at, scheduled change).

items.name: NextForced
docs: next block number where we can force a change.

items.name: Stalled
docs: `true` if we are currently stalled.

items.name: CurrentSetId
docs: The number of changes (both in terms of keys and underlying economic responsibilities)
in the "set" of Grandpa validators from genesis.

items.name: SetIdSession
docs: A mapping from grandpa set ID to the index of the *most recent* session for which its
members were responsible.
This is only used for validating equivocation proofs. An equivocation proof must
contains a key-ownership proof for a given session, therefore we need a way to tie
together sessions and GRANDPA set ids, i.e. we need to validate that a validator
was the owner of a given key on a given session, and what the active set ID was
during that session.
TWOX-NOTE: `SetId` is not under user control.

items.name: Authorities
docs: The current list of authorities.

constants.name: MaxAuthorities
docs: Max Authorities in use

constants.name: MaxNominators
docs: The maximum number of nominators for each validator.

constants.name: MaxSetIdSessionEntries
docs: The maximum number of entries to keep in the set id to session index mapping.
Since the `SetIdSession` map is only used for validating equivocations this
value should relate to the bonding duration of whatever staking system is
being used (if any). If equivocation handling is not enabled then this value
can be zero.

items.name: ProposalCount
docs: Number of proposals that have been made.

items.name: Proposals
docs: Proposals that have been made.

items.name: Deactivated

items.name: Approvals
docs: Proposal indices that have been approved but not yet awarded.

items.name: SpendCount
docs: The count of spends that have been made.

items.name: Spends
docs: Spends that have been approved and being processed.

constants.name: ProposalBond
docs: Fraction of a proposal's value that should be bonded in order to place the proposal.
An accepted proposal gets these back. A rejected proposal does not.

constants.name: ProposalBondMinimum
docs: Minimum amount of funds that should be placed in a deposit for making a proposal.

constants.name: ProposalBondMaximum
docs: Maximum amount of funds that should be placed in a deposit for making a proposal.

constants.name: SpendPeriod
docs: Period between successive spends.

constants.name: Burn
docs: Percentage of spare funds (if any) that are burnt per spend period.

constants.name: PalletId
docs: The treasury's pallet id, used for deriving its sovereign account ID.

constants.name: MaxApprovals
docs: The maximum number of approvals that can wait in the spending queue.
NOTE: This parameter is also used within the Bounties Pallet extension if enabled.

constants.name: PayoutPeriod
docs: The period during which an approved treasury spend has to be claimed.

items.name: ConversionRateToNative
docs: Maps an asset to its fixed point representation in the native balance.
E.g. `native_amount = asset_amount * ConversionRateToNative::<T>::get(asset_kind)`

items.name: PristineCode
docs: A mapping from a contract's code hash to its code.

items.name: CodeInfoOf
docs: A mapping from a contract's code hash to its code info.

items.name: Nonce
docs: This is a **monotonic** counter incremented on contract instantiation.
This is used in order to generate unique trie ids for contracts.
The trie id of a new contract is calculated from hash(account_id, nonce).
The nonce is required because otherwise the following sequence would lead to
a possible collision of storage:
1. Create a new contract.
2. Terminate the contract.
3. Immediately recreate the contract with the same account_id.
This is bad because the contents of a trie are deleted lazily and there might be
storage of the old instantiation still in it when the new contract is created. Please
note that we can't replace the counter by the block number because the sequence above
can happen in the same block. We also can't keep the account counter in memory only
because storage is the only way to communicate across different extrinsics in the
same block.
# Note
Do not use it to determine the number of contracts. It won't be decremented if
a contract is destroyed.

items.name: ContractInfoOf
docs: The code associated with a given account.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE since `AccountId` is a secure hash.

items.name: DeletionQueue
docs: Evicted contracts that await child trie deletion.
Child trie deletion is a heavy operation depending on the amount of storage items
stored in said trie. Therefore this operation is performed lazily in `on_idle`.

items.name: DeletionQueueCounter
docs: A pair of monotonic counters used to track the latest contract marked for deletion
and the latest deleted contract in queue.

items.name: MigrationInProgress
docs: A migration can span across multiple blocks. This storage defines a cursor to track the
progress of the migration, enabling us to resume from the last completed position.

constants.name: Schedule
docs: Cost schedule and limits.

constants.name: DepositPerByte
docs: The amount of balance a caller has to pay for each byte of storage.
# Note
Changing this value for an existing chain might need a storage migration.

constants.name: DefaultDepositLimit
docs: Fallback value to limit the storage deposit if it's not being set by the caller.

constants.name: DepositPerItem
docs: The amount of balance a caller has to pay for each storage item.
# Note
Changing this value for an existing chain might need a storage migration.

constants.name: CodeHashLockupDepositPercent
docs: The percentage of the storage deposit that should be held for using a code hash.
Instantiating a contract, or calling [`chain_extension::Ext::add_delegate_dependency`]
protects the code from being removed. In order to prevent abuse these actions are
protected with a percentage of the code deposit.

constants.name: MaxCodeLen
docs: The maximum length of a contract code in bytes.
The value should be chosen carefully taking into the account the overall memory limit
your runtime has, as well as the [maximum allowed callstack
depth](#associatedtype.CallStack). Look into the `integrity_test()` for some insights.

constants.name: MaxStorageKeyLen
docs: The maximum allowable length in bytes for storage keys.

constants.name: MaxDelegateDependencies
docs: The maximum number of delegate_dependencies that a contract can lock with
[`chain_extension::Ext::add_delegate_dependency`].

constants.name: UnsafeUnstableInterface
docs: Make contract callable functions marked as `#[unstable]` available.
Contracts that use `#[unstable]` functions won't be able to be uploaded unless
this is set to `true`. This is only meant for testnets and dev nodes in order to
experiment with new features.
# Warning
Do **not** set to `true` on productions chains.

constants.name: MaxDebugBufferLen
docs: The maximum length of the debug buffer in bytes.

constants.name: Environment
docs: Type that bundles together all the runtime configurable interface types.
This is not a real config. We just mention the type here as constant so that
its type appears in the metadata. Only valid value is `()`.

items.name: Key
docs: The `AccountId` of the sudo key.

items.name: HeartbeatAfter
docs: The block number after which it's ok to send heartbeats in the current
session.
At the beginning of each session we set this to a value that should fall
roughly in the middle of the session duration. The idea is to first wait for
the validators to produce a block in the current session, so that the
heartbeat later on will not be necessary.
This value will only be used as a fallback if we fail to get a proper session
progress estimate from `NextSessionRotation`, as those estimates should be
more accurate then the value we calculate for `HeartbeatAfter`.

items.name: Keys
docs: The current set of keys that may issue a heartbeat.

items.name: ReceivedHeartbeats
docs: For each session index, we keep a mapping of `SessionIndex` and `AuthIndex`.

items.name: AuthoredBlocks
docs: For each session index, we keep a mapping of `ValidatorId<T>` to the
number of blocks authored by the given authority.

constants.name: UnsignedPriority
docs: A configuration for base priority of unsigned transactions.
This is exposed so that it can be tuned for particular runtime, when
multiple pallets send unsigned transactions.

items.name: Keys
docs: Keys of the current authority set.

items.name: NextKeys
docs: Keys of the next authority set.

items.name: Reports
docs: The primary structure that holds all offence records keyed by report identifiers.

items.name: ConcurrentReportsIndex
docs: A vector of reports of the same kind that happened at the same time slot.

items.name: RandomMaterial
docs: Series of block headers from the last 81 blocks that acts as random seed material. This
is arranged as a ring buffer with `block_number % 81` being the index into the `Vec` of
the oldest hash.

items.name: IdentityOf
docs: Information that is pertinent to identify the entity behind an account.
TWOX-NOTE: OK  `AccountId` is a secure hash.

items.name: SuperOf
docs: The super-identity of an alternative "sub" identity together with its name, within that
context. If the account is not some other account's sub-identity, then just `None`.

items.name: SubsOf
docs: Alternative "sub" identities of this account.
The first item is the deposit, the second is a vector of the accounts.
TWOX-NOTE: OK  `AccountId` is a secure hash.

items.name: Registrars
docs: The set of registrars. Not expected to get very big as can only be added through a
special origin (likely a council motion).
The index into this can be cast to `RegistrarIndex` to get a valid value.

constants.name: BasicDeposit
docs: The amount held on deposit for a registered identity

constants.name: ByteDeposit
docs: The amount held on deposit per encoded byte for a registered identity.

constants.name: SubAccountDeposit
docs: The amount held on deposit for a registered subaccount. This should account for the fact
that one storage item's value will increase by the size of an account ID, and there will
be another trie item whose value is the size of an account ID plus 32 bytes.

constants.name: MaxSubAccounts
docs: The maximum number of sub-accounts allowed per identified account.

constants.name: MaxRegistrars
docs: Maxmimum number of registrars allowed in the system. Needed to bound the complexity
of, e.g., updating judgements.

items.name: Parameters

items.name: Pot
docs: Amount of our account balance that is specifically for the next round's bid(s).

items.name: Founder
docs: The first member.

items.name: Head
docs: The most primary from the most recently approved rank 0 members in the society.

items.name: Rules
docs: A hash of the rules of this society concerning membership. Can only be set once and
only by the founder.

items.name: Members
docs: The current members and their rank. Doesn't include `SuspendedMembers`.

items.name: Payouts
docs: Information regarding rank-0 payouts, past and future.

items.name: MemberCount
docs: The number of items in `Members` currently. (Doesn't include `SuspendedMembers`.)

items.name: MemberByIndex
docs: The current items in `Members` keyed by their unique index. Keys are densely populated
`0..MemberCount` (does not include `MemberCount`).

items.name: RoundCount

items.name: Bids

items.name: Skeptic
docs: The current skeptic.

items.name: VoteClearCursor
docs: Clear-cursor for Vote, map from Candidate -> (Maybe) Cursor.

items.name: NextHead
docs: At the end of the claim period, this contains the most recently approved members (along with
their bid and round ID) who is from the most recent round with the lowest bid. They will
become the new `Head`.

items.name: ChallengeRoundCount
docs: The number of challenge rounds there have been. Used to identify stale DefenderVotes.

items.name: Defending
docs: The defending member currently being challenged, along with a running tally of votes.

items.name: DefenderVotes
docs: Votes for the defender, keyed by challenge round.

constants.name: PalletId
docs: The societies's pallet id

constants.name: GraceStrikes

constants.name: PeriodSpend

`ClaimPeriod`, this sums to the number of blocks between candidate intake periods.

docs: The number of blocks on which new candidates can claim their membership and be the
named head.

constants.name: MaxLockDuration
docs: The maximum duration of the payout lock.

constants.name: ChallengePeriod
docs: The number of blocks between membership challenges.

constants.name: MaxPayouts
docs: The maximum number of payouts a member may have waiting unclaimed.

constants.name: MaxBids
docs: The maximum number of bids at once.

items.name: Recoverable
docs: The set of recoverable accounts and their recovery configuration.

items.name: ActiveRecoveries
docs: Active recovery attempts.
First account is the account to be recovered, and the second account
is the user trying to recover the account.

items.name: Proxy
docs: The list of allowed proxy accounts.
Map from the user who can access it to the recovered account.

constants.name: ConfigDepositBase
docs: The base amount of currency needed to reserve for creating a recovery configuration.
This is held for an additional storage item whose value size is
`2 + sizeof(BlockNumber, Balance)` bytes.

constants.name: FriendDepositFactor
docs: The amount of currency needed per additional user when creating a recovery
configuration.
This is held for adding `sizeof(AccountId)` bytes more into a pre-existing storage
value.

constants.name: MaxFriends
docs: The maximum amount of friends allowed in a recovery configuration.
NOTE: The threshold programmed in this Pallet uses u16, so it does
not really make sense to have a limit here greater than u16::MAX.
But also, that is a lot more than you should probably set this value
to anyway...

constants.name: RecoveryDeposit
docs: The base amount of currency needed to reserve for starting a recovery.
This is primarily held for deterring malicious recovery attempts, and should
have a value large enough that a bad actor would choose not to place this
deposit. It also acts to fund additional storage item whose value size is
`sizeof(BlockNumber, Balance + T * AccountId)` bytes. Where T is a configurable
threshold.

items.name: Vesting
docs: Information regarding the vesting of a given account.

items.name: StorageVersion
docs: Storage version of the pallet.
New networks start with latest version, as determined by the genesis build.

constants.name: MinVestedTransfer
docs: The minimum amount transferred to call `vested_transfer`.

items.name: Agenda
docs: Items to be executed, indexed by the block number that they should be executed on.

items.name: Lookup
docs: Lookup from a name to the block number and index of the task.
For v3 -> v4 the previously unbounded identities are Blake2-256 hashed to form the v4
identities.

constants.name: MaximumWeight
docs: The maximum weight that may be scheduled per block for any dispatchables.

constants.name: MaxScheduledPerBlock
docs: The maximum number of scheduled calls in the queue for a single block.
NOTE:
+ Dependent pallets' benchmarks might require a higher limit for the setting. Set a
higher limit under `runtime-benchmarks` feature.

items.name: Compute
docs: The proportion of the remaining `ref_time` to consume during `on_idle`.
`1.0` is mapped to `100%`. Must be at most [`crate::RESOURCE_HARD_LIMIT`]. Setting this to
over `1.0` could stall the chain.

items.name: TrashData
docs: Storage map used for wasting proof size.
It contains no meaningful data - hence the name "Trash". The maximal number of entries is
set to 65k, which is just below the next jump at 16^4. This is important to reduce the proof
size benchmarking overestimate. The assumption here is that we won't have more than 65k *
1KiB = 65MiB of proof size wasting in practice. However, this limit is not enforced, so the
pallet would also work out of the box with more entries, but its benchmarked proof weight
would possibly be underestimated in that case.

constants.name: BagThresholds
docs: The list of thresholds separating the various bags.
Ids are separated into unsorted bags according to their score. This specifies the
thresholds separating the bags. An id's bag is the largest bag for which the id's score
is less than or equal to its upper threshold.
When ids are iterated, higher bags are iterated completely before lower bags. This means
that iteration is _semi-sorted_: ids of higher score tend to come before ids of lower
score, but peer ids within a particular bag are sorted in insertion order.
# Expressing the constant
This constant must be sorted in strictly increasing order. Duplicate items are not
permitted.
There is an implied upper limit of `Score::MAX`; that value does not need to be
specified within the bag. For any two threshold lists, if one ends with
`Score::MAX`, the other one does not, and they are otherwise equal, the two
lists will behave identically.
# Calculation
It is recommended to generate the set of thresholds in a geometric series, such that
there exists some constant ratio such that `threshold[k + 1] == (threshold[k] *
constant_ratio).max(threshold[k] + 1)` for all `k`.
The helpers in the `/utils/frame/generate-bags` module can simplify this calculation.
# Examples
- If `BagThresholds::get().is_empty()`, then all ids are put into the same bag, and
iteration is strictly in insertion order.
- If `BagThresholds::get().len() == 64`, and the thresholds are determined according to
the procedure given above, then the constant ratio is equal to 2.
- If `BagThresholds::get().len() == 200`, and the thresholds are determined according to
the procedure given above, then the constant ratio is approximately equal to 1.248.
- If the threshold list begins `[1, 2, 3, ...]`, then an id with score 0 or 1 will fall
into bag 0, an id with score 2 will fall into bag 1, etc.
# Migration
In the event that this list ever changes, a copy of the old bags list must be retained.
With that `List::migrate` can be called, which will perform the appropriate migration.

constants.name: MaxKeyLen
docs: Maximal number of bytes that a key can have.
FRAME itself does not limit the key length.
The concrete value must therefore depend on your storage usage.
A [`frame_support::storage::StorageNMap`] for example can have an arbitrary number of
keys which are then hashed and concatenated, resulting in arbitrarily long keys.
Use the *state migration RPC* to retrieve the length of the longest key in your
storage: <https://github.com/paritytech/substrate/issues/11642>
The migration will halt with a `Halted` event if this value is too small.
Since there is no real penalty from over-estimating, it is advised to use a large
value. The default is 512 byte.
Some key lengths for reference:
- [`frame_support::storage::StorageValue`]: 32 byte
- [`frame_support::storage::StorageMap`]: 64 byte
- [`frame_support::storage::StorageDoubleMap`]: 96 byte
For more info see
<https://www.shawntabrizi.com/substrate/querying-substrate-storage-via-rpc/>

docs: Map from a pool member account to their opted claim permission.

constants.name: PalletId
docs: The nomination pool's pallet id.

constants.name: MaxPointsToBalance
docs: The maximum pool points-to-balance ratio that an `open` pool can have.
This is important in the event slashing takes place and the pool's points-to-balance
ratio becomes disproportional.
Moreover, this relates to the `RewardCounter` type as well, as the arithmetic operations
are a function of number of points, and by setting this value to e.g. 10, you ensure
that the total number of points in the system are at most 10 times the total_issuance of
the chain, in the absolute worse case.
For a value of 10, the threshold would be a pool points-to-balance ratio of 10:1.
Such a scenario would also be the equivalent of the pool being 90% slashed.

constants.name: MaxUnbonding
docs: The maximum number of simultaneous unbonding chunks that can exist per member.

items.name: ReferendumCount
docs: The next free referendum index, aka the number of referenda started so far.

items.name: ReferendumInfoFor
docs: Information concerning any given referendum.

items.name: TrackQueue
docs: The sorted list of referenda ready to be decided but not yet being decided, ordered by
conviction-weighted approvals.
This should be empty if `DecidingCount` is less than `TrackInfo::max_deciding`.

items.name: DecidingCount
docs: The number of referenda being decided currently.

items.name: MetadataOf
docs: The metadata is a general information concerning the referendum.
The `Hash` refers to the preimage of the `Preimages` provider which can be a JSON
dump or IPFS hash of a JSON file.
Consider a garbage collection for a metadata of finished referendums to `unrequest` (remove)
large preimages.

constants.name: SubmissionDeposit
docs: The minimum amount to be used as a deposit for a public referendum proposal.

constants.name: MaxQueued
docs: Maximum size of the referendum queue for a single track.

constants.name: UndecidingTimeout
docs: The number of blocks after submission that a referendum must begin being decided by.
Once this passes, then anyone may cancel the referendum.

constants.name: AlarmInterval
docs: Quantization level for the referendum wakeup scheduler. A higher number will result in
fewer storage reads/writes needed for smaller voters, but also result in delays to the
automatic referendum status changes. Explicit servicing instructions are unaffected.

constants.name: Tracks
docs: Information concerning the different referendum tracks.

items.name: MemberCount
docs: The number of members in the collective who have at least the rank according to the index
of the vec.

items.name: Members
docs: The current members of the collective.

items.name: IdToIndex
docs: The index of each ranks's member into the group of members who have at least that rank.

items.name: IndexToId
docs: The members in the collective by index. All indices in the range `0..MemberCount` will
return `Some`, however a member's index is not guaranteed to remain unchanged over time.

items.name: Voting
docs: Votes on a given proposal, if it is ongoing.

items.name: Pools
docs: Map from `PoolAssetId` to `PoolInfo`. This establishes whether a pool has been officially
created rather than people sending tokens directly to a pool's public account.

items.name: NextPoolAssetId
docs: Stores the `PoolAssetId` that is going to be used for the next lp token.
This gets incremented whenever a new lp pool is created.

constants.name: LPFee
docs: A % the liquidity providers will take of every swap. Represents 10ths of a percent.

constants.name: PoolSetupFee
docs: A one-time fee to setup the pool.

constants.name: LiquidityWithdrawalFee
docs: A fee to withdraw the liquidity.

constants.name: MintMinLiquidity
docs: The minimum LP token amount that could be minted. Ameliorates rounding errors.

constants.name: MaxSwapPathLength
docs: The max number of hops in a swap.

constants.name: PalletId
docs: The pallet's id, used for deriving its sovereign account ID.

constants.name: AllowMultiAssetPools
docs: A setting to allow creating pools with both non-native assets.

items.name: Head
docs: The current "head of the queue" being unstaked.
The head in itself can be a batch of up to [`Config::BatchSize`] stakers.

items.name: Queue
docs: The map of all accounts wishing to be unstaked.
Keeps track of `AccountId` wishing to unstake and it's corresponding deposit.

items.name: CounterForQueue
docs: Counter for the related counted storage map

items.name: ErasToCheckPerBlock
docs: Number of eras to check per block.
If set to 0, this pallet does absolutely nothing. Cannot be set to more than
[`Config::MaxErasToCheckPerBlock`].
Based on the amount of weight available at [`Pallet::on_idle`], up to this many eras are
checked. The checking is represented by updating [`UnstakeRequest::checked`], which is
stored in [`Head`].

constants.name: Deposit
docs: Deposit to take for unstaking, to make sure we're able to slash the it in order to cover
the costs of resources on unsuccessful unstake.

items.name: BookStateFor
docs: The index of the first and last (non-empty) pages.

items.name: ServiceHead
docs: The origin at which we should begin servicing.

items.name: Pages
docs: The map of page indices to pages.

constants.name: HeapSize
docs: The size of the page; this implies the maximum message size which can be sent.
A good value depends on the expected message sizes, their weights, the weight that is
available for processing them and the maximal needed message size. The maximal message
size is slightly lower than this as defined by [`MaxMessageLenOf`].

constants.name: MaxStale
docs: The maximum number of stale pages (i.e. of overweight messages) allowed before culling
can happen. Once there are more stale pages than this, then historical pages may be
dropped, even if they contain unprocessed overweight messages.

constants.name: ServiceWeight
docs: The amount of weight (if any) which should be provided to the message queue for
servicing enqueued items.
This may be legitimately `None` in the case that you will call
`ServiceQueues::service_queues` manually.

items.name: UnboundedValue
docs: A value without a MEL bound.

items.name: BoundedValue
docs: A value with a MEL bound of 32 byte.

items.name: LargeValue
docs: 4MiB value.

items.name: Map1M
docs: A map with a maximum of 1M entries.

items.name: Map16M
docs: A map with a maximum of 16M entries.

items.name: PausedCalls
docs: The set of calls that are explicitly paused.

constants.name: MaxNameLen
docs: Maximum length for pallet name and call name SCALE encoded string names.
TOO LONG NAMES WILL BE TREATED AS PAUSED.

items.name: EnteredUntil
docs: Contains the last block number that the safe-mode will remain entered in.
Set to `None` when safe-mode is exited.
Safe-mode is automatically exited when the current block number exceeds this value.

items.name: Deposits
docs: Holds the reserve that was taken from an account at a specific block number.
This helps governance to have an overview of outstanding deposits that should be returned or
slashed.

constants.name: EnterDuration
docs: For how many blocks the safe-mode will be entered by [`Pallet::enter`].

constants.name: ExtendDuration
docs: For how many blocks the safe-mode can be extended by each [`Pallet::extend`] call.
This does not impose a hard limit as the safe-mode can be extended multiple times.

constants.name: EnterDepositAmount
docs: The amount that will be reserved upon calling [`Pallet::enter`].
`None` disallows permissionlessly enabling the safe-mode and is a sane default.

constants.name: ExtendDepositAmount
docs: The amount that will be reserved upon calling [`Pallet::extend`].
`None` disallows permissionlessly extending the safe-mode and is a sane default.

constants.name: ReleaseDelay
docs: The minimal duration a deposit will remain reserved after safe-mode is entered or
extended, unless [`Pallet::force_release_deposit`] is successfully called sooner.
Every deposit is tied to a specific activation or extension, thus each deposit can be
released independently after the delay for it has passed.
`None` disallows permissionlessly releasing the safe-mode deposits and is a sane
default.

constants.name: StatementCost
docs: Min balance for priority statements.

constants.name: ByteCost
docs: Cost of data byte used for priority calculation.

constants.name: MinAllowedStatements
docs: Minimum number of statements allowed per account.

constants.name: MaxAllowedStatements
docs: Maximum number of statements allowed per account.

constants.name: MinAllowedBytes
docs: Minimum data bytes allowed per account.

constants.name: MaxAllowedBytes
docs: Maximum data bytes allowed per account.

items.name: Configuration
docs: The current configuration of this pallet.

items.name: Reservations
docs: The Polkadot Core reservations (generally tasked with the maintenance of System Chains).

items.name: Leases
docs: The Polkadot Core legacy leases.

items.name: Status
docs: The current status of miscellaneous subsystems of this pallet.

items.name: SaleInfo
docs: The details of the current sale, including its properties and status.

items.name: AllowedRenewals
docs: Records of allowed renewals.

items.name: Regions
docs: The current (unassigned) Regions.

items.name: Workplan
docs: The work we plan on having each core do at a particular time in the future.

items.name: Workload
docs: The current workload of each core. This gets updated with workplan as timeslices pass.

items.name: InstaPoolContribution
docs: Record of a single contribution to the Instantaneous Coretime Pool.

items.name: InstaPoolIo
docs: Record of Coretime entering or leaving the Instantaneous Coretime Pool.

items.name: InstaPoolHistory
docs: Total InstaPool rewards for each Timeslice and the number of core parts which contributed.

constants.name: PalletId
docs: Identifier from which the internal Pot is generated.

constants.name: TimeslicePeriod
docs: Number of Relay-chain blocks per timeslice.

constants.name: MaxLeasedCores
docs: Maximum number of legacy leases.

constants.name: MaxReservedCores
docs: Maximum number of system cores.

items.name: CurrentSessionIndex
docs: Index of the current session. This may be offset relative to the session index tracked by
eg `pallet_session`; mixnet session indices are independent.

items.name: CurrentSessionStartBlock
docs: Block in which the current session started.

items.name: NextAuthorityIds
docs: Authority list for the next session.

items.name: Mixnodes
docs: Mixnode sets by session index. Only the mixnode sets for the previous, current, and next
sessions are kept; older sets are discarded.
The mixnodes in each set are keyed by authority index so we can easily check if an
authority has registered a mixnode. The authority indices should only be used during
registration; the authority indices for the very first session are made up.

constants.name: MaxAuthorities
docs: The maximum number of authorities per session.

constants.name: MaxExternalAddressSize
docs: The maximum size of one of a mixnode's external addresses.

constants.name: MaxExternalAddressesPerMixnode
docs: The maximum number of external addresses for a mixnode.

constants.name: NumCoverToCurrentBlocks
docs: Length of the first phase of each session (`CoverToCurrent`), in blocks.

constants.name: NumRequestsToCurrentBlocks
docs: Length of the second phase of each session (`RequestsToCurrent`), in blocks.

constants.name: NumCoverToPrevBlocks
docs: Length of the third phase of each session (`CoverToPrev`), in blocks.

constants.name: NumRegisterStartSlackBlocks
docs: The number of "slack" blocks at the start of each session, during which
[`maybe_register`](Pallet::maybe_register) will not attempt to post registration
transactions.

constants.name: NumRegisterEndSlackBlocks
docs: The number of "slack" blocks at the end of each session.
[`maybe_register`](Pallet::maybe_register) will try to register before this slack
period, but may post registration transactions during the slack period as a last
resort.

constants.name: RegistrationPriority
docs: Priority of unsigned transactions used to register mixnodes.

constants.name: MinMixnodes
docs: Minimum number of mixnodes. If there are fewer than this many mixnodes registered for a
session, the mixnet will not be active during the session.
